    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "There is also the question of separating out the \"language\" (Python 2,\nPython 3, Julia) from the \"project (IPython, Julia, etc.). I would prefer\nthis as it allows different projects to provide the same language and gives\nus the information needed for users to pick the right one. Also, I think\nour main UI for kernel selection should be, to first order based on the\n_language_ not the project.\n\nOn Wed, Oct 22, 2014 at 2:36 PM, Thomas Kluyver notifications@github.com\nwrote:\n\n> I've noticed recently that kernelspecs at present are a combination of two\n> very different kinds of information: how to start a given kernel, and how\n> to treat code written in the language of that kernelspec. So far this isn't\n> a practical problem, but it is a bit of a code smell, and if we're going to\n> rethink it, we really need to do it before release.\n> \n> The three options I'm considering are:\n> 1. Leave everything as is.\n> 2. Leave the language info in the kernelspec, but move it into a sub\n>    dictionary, and store it separately in notebook metadata - kernelspec in nb\n>    metadata would just contain name and display name, and language_info would\n>    be a separate top level key.\n> 3. Move language info to the kernel info request, so kernelspecs\n>    really just describe how to start a kernel: the frontend asks the kernel\n>    for all info about its language. Metadata storage would be as 2. This feels\n>    more correct, but it would also be more disruptive. This would mean that,\n>    when creating a new notebook, highlighting would briefly be wrong until the\n>    kernel came up. Existing notebooks would not suffer, because the language\n>    info would be in metadata.\n> \n> Ping kernel authors @stevengj https://github.com/stevengj, @gibiansky\n> https://github.com/gibiansky, @blink1073 https://github.com/blink1073,\n> @dsblank https://github.com/dsblank, and @ellisonbg\n> https://github.com/ellisonbg who has been thinking about delayed kernel\n> start.\n> \n> â€”\n> Reply to this email directly or view it on GitHub\n> https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/6776.\n\n## \n\nBrian E. Granger\nCal Poly State University, San Luis Obispo\n@ellisonbg on Twitter and GitHub\nbgranger@calpoly.edu and ellisonbg@gmail.com\n"
  },
